","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3754"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38775"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a two-week history of increasing fatigue and pallor. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. He has no recent travel history or exposure to illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale but well with vital signs within normal limits. He has no lymphadenopathy or hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 85 g/L (115-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean cell volume 88 fL (75-95)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count 6.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.5-13.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count 250 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-450)\u003Cbr /\u003EReticulocyte count 8.5% (0.5-2.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EDirect antiglobulin test (DAT) IgG 3+\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the reticulocytosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron deficiency anaemia","Transient erythroblastopenia of childhood","Aplastic anaemia","Acute leukaemia","Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with normocytic anaemia, a markedly elevated reticulocyte count, and a positive direct antiglobulin test (DAT), indicating immune-mediated red cell destruction. The absence of organomegaly and normal white cell and platelet counts help narrow the differential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, while common in children, typically presents with microcytic anaemia (low MCV). Although reticulocyte count may be mildly elevated, it would not reach the levels seen here due to limited iron availability for erythropoiesis. Additionally, the DAT would be negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient erythroblastopenia of childhood\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by decreased red cell production and would present with a low reticulocyte count during the acute phase. While reticulocytosis may be observed during recovery from transient erythroblastopenia of childhood, the positive DAT makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E involves bone marrow failure affecting all cell lines. It would present with pancytopenia and low reticulocyte count, not isolated anaemia with reticulocytosis. The DAT would also be negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with pancytopenia, blast cells on blood film, and low reticulocyte count due to bone marrow infiltration. The normal white cell count, absence of other cytopenias, and positive DAT make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with anaemia, elevated reticulocyte count (\u003E3%), and normal cell indices. The positive DAT (IgG 3+) confirms the presence of antibodies on red blood cells, establishing the diagnosis of immune-mediated haemolysis. The bone marrow responds appropriately to red cell destruction by increasing erythropoiesis, leading to reticulocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Reticulocyte count and indices are crucial first-line investigations in the evaluation of childhood anaemia","High reticulocyte count with anaemia suggests increased red cell destruction or blood loss","A positive direct antiglobulin test (DAT) confirms immune-mediated haemolysis in a child with anaemia and reticulocytosis"],"references":["Parodi E, Romano F, Ramenghi U. How We Use Reticulocyte Parameters in Workup and Management of Pediatric Hematologic Diseases. Front Pediatr. 2020 Dec 4;8:588617. doi: 10.3389/fped.2020.588617. PMID: 33344383; PMCID: PMC7746543."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14679"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91022"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T17:24:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T17:26:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108653"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{